reviews.text:
Charlie Bird is very much a presentation first establishment in my eyes. It's not bad by any means, but I am pretty disappointed especially since the food looks better than it actually tastes (not bad, just very average).

Razor clams: Tangy, slightly savory, but you should prob pass on it at $7/pp.

Burrata Crostini: it looks amazing, but there was no flavor. I literally only tasted the crostini.

Farro Salad: Nice composition of flavors, but it doesn't really stand out.

Tuscan Fried Chicken: Fairly flavorful and juicy, the best of the appetizers. But honestly, you are much better off going to a restaurant dedicated to fried chicken.

French Fries: Actually really good, crispy and salty. If I ever came back, I would always order these with my meal.

Chicken Milanese: ....the little side salad and the jam was the best part. The crust is the milanese is crispy and salted well, the chicken itself is cooked well..... But the chicken itself was not seasoned.

The portions were okay overall.

I'm not a picky eater by any means, but I was pretty disappointed overall with this meal. Maybe I was there the wrong day, but I left fairly disappointed. Although I rated it a 4 overall by NY standards, I would personally consider the food a 3/5 as I doubt I would ever return myself.

reviews.text:
We dined at Carbone many years ago, before all the hype, and at the time thought it was a solid experience with generous portions. This visit, however, I completely understand the buzz.

Despite being 20 minutes late to our reservation, we were graciously seated on a packed Saturday night — a great first impression. The Caesar salad was phenomenal, with bold flavors and an unforgettable sauce. The beef tartare and spicy vodka rigatoni were definite standouts.

The ribeye was good but felt a bit heavy with the sauce. Dessert more than made up for it — the carrot cake with ginger ice cream was excellent.

What truly sets Carbone apart is the ambiance. Cozy, intimate, and beautifully styled with real candles and timeless music, it feels like stepping into a glamorous 1960s supper club. Elegant, lively, and full of character — a memorable dining experience from start to finish.
reviews.author: Yuliya Lubin

reviews.text:
Carbone exceeded every expectation while we celebrated my husband’s birthday here! From the moment we arrived, the service was impeccable from all the staffs: warm, welcoming.

This restaurant is incredibly hard to get into, and it absolutely lives up to the hype. The energy is electric, the room is buzzing, and the hospitality feels elevated and personal. Eddie was our main guy and was phenomenal! He so attentive and thoughtful. Michuel was also wonderful, making sure everything flowed seamlessly.

The food was delicious, rich, and comforting. The experience as a whole felt special from start to finish.

If you’re celebrating something meaningful or just want to experience one of NYC’s most iconic restaurants, Carbone is worth every bit of the hype.

reviews.text:
Excellent classic Italian.

Heard a lot about Via Carota and Chef Jody Williams, and when it was recognized by North America’s Best 50 last year, I finally decided to give it a try. We came for a weekday lunch and were seated without a wait at the communal table in the back. Still thoughtfully spaced, with an empty seat between groups.

Given Chef Williams’s background, the menu was a mix of Tuscan and Roman. Territory I’m fairly familiar with coming from Boston. We ordered a few classics like the grilled artichoke, cacio e pepe, and potato ravioli ragu (daily special). Portions were a bit small for the price, but the execution was flawless.

One thing we really loved was their iconic cacio e pepe. Most trattorias I’ve been to rely on dried pasta for a firmer al dente bite, but Chef Williams used fresh pasta across the menu. And it worked beautifully here. Silky and supple, yet still retaining a satisfying snap. More importantly, the sauce had a bold, unapologetic pepperiness that I’ve never felt before from other trattorias in the U.S.

Perhaps Via Carota might not be a place people chase for excitement, but it’s the kind of restaurant I’d regularly visit if it was in my neighborhood. Highly recommend giving them a try for comforting, well-executed Italian classics.

reviews.text:
Emilio’s Ballato
55 E. Houston St.
New York, NY 10012

This restaurant is high profile.  Several celebrities have frequented this spot and the dining area has photos of all the icons who visited.

There is usually a line; all customers are required to wait outside because there is no indoor lobby.

The focaccia bread was one of the best starters I ever had.  It especially went well with olive oil.

The cutlet was gigantic.  It was pounded thin with crispy edges.  While there was a decent ratio of sauce, it was too sweet for my taste.

For the most part, I enjoyed the cutlet.  However, a major disadvantage is that pasta is not included; I would have to buy a separate entrée.  There is not even an option to purchase a side of pasta for an up charge.  I would have comprised and paid an additional cost even though the lone cutlet was a whopping $42.

#emiliosballato #emiliosballatonyc #chickenparm
reviews.author: Jeff T. Critic

reviews.text:
Emilio’s is an iconic New York City spot. From the moment you walk in, you’re surrounded by history the walls are filled with photos of famous and notorious people who have visited over the years.

During our visit, while waiting to be seated outside, we even saw one of The Sopranos actors. The main actor walked out of the restaurant, which was a cool moment. The only downside was the seating process for dining. You have to wait outside in line until a table opens, and in the middle of a New York City winter, that was rough. We waited over an hour and were honestly frozen by the time we got in.

That said, once inside, it was worth it. The restaurant is small, with around ten tables, but it’s very warm and welcoming. The staff was kind, the food was good, and there were plenty of Italian options along with great wine. The vibe was cozy, lively, and perfect for conversation.

reviews.text:

reviews.text:
This CoMPANY SHORT CHANGES ARTIST
I worked on this project for three days in 30-degree weather, commuting over an hour each way by bus while carrying 60 pounds of equipment. During that time, I completed more work than originally agreed upon, including four full panels and an additional smaller panel.

Due to existing vinyl on the windows, the original design could not physically fit as planned. I communicated this clearly, improvised, and updated them throughout the process. The only unfinished element was an additional image planned for the opposite side of the building, which I was scheduled to complete the following Monday.
Unfortunately, I came down with a respiratory infection and informed them that I wouldn’t be able to return.

Despite the substantial amount of completed work, they chose to withhold $50 from my payment, claiming the project didn’t fully match “their vision.”mind you, I had adjusted the final price because I didn’t finish the final panel on the other side.

Communication around payment was unnecessarily difficult, and the decision to short an independent artist over such a small amount was disappointing—especially for a company that claims to support and uplift people.

$50 won’t break me, but the choice to withhold it speaks volumes.

I understand it was raining yesterday and the café was packed, but that should never be an excuse for being rude to customers.
1. When I placed my order at the counter, the staff almost throwing the receipt at me.
2. I ordered a mocha latte instead-they told me they don't have matcha, but what I received looked and tasted like a plain latte. When I asked if it was actually a mocha, I was told
“Yes, that’s mocha.”
it wasn’t, I brought the paper receipt and asked again and the same staff to squeeze chocolate syrup into my cup right in front of me and say, “It’s mocha.”
This kind of service is unbelievably unprofessional and disrespectful.
Overall, coffee was good and I’ve always enjoyed Devoción, but after this experience, I won’t be returning—nor will I be recommending the new location to anyone. I feel so sorry to my friends.
reviews.author: Suha Kim

personalization.forUser: Given Alex's preferences, the Brooklyn Roasting Company's dedication to quality coffee may provide a good work environment.

places.address: 1 Clinton St, Brooklyn, NY 11201, USA

reviews.text:
Decent laptop friendly cafe. The coffee (pistachio latte) wasn’t mind blowing, and it was quite high end ($7). The lighting is super dark. The wifi didn’t work but you can connect to the library wifi.

They have a small baked goods selection
reviews.author: Isabella Grandic

reviews.text: It is a gem among coffee shops. From their exceptional coffee and friendly staff to their commitment to sustainability, they have created a truly remarkable establishment. I highly recommend paying them a visit if you're in the area. You won't be disappointed! The cozy ambiance of the café provided the perfect setting to relax, catch up with friends, or enjoy some quiet time with a good book. The colorful decor and comfortable seating added to the overall charm of the place.
reviews.author: Victoria Magon

reviews.text:
12/10/25, 8am. Walk in, not even a friendly greeting. Ordered a vanilla late to stay, got a to go cup. Way way too sweet.

Waited 10minutes for one late. Went to to ask about it and she just said she called it 3 times, very arrogant. This after I left a tip.

Management should implement some kind of system that calls out names or numbers.
reviews.author: Marco Le Roux

personalization.forUser: The relaxed atmosphere of Sippy Cafe may be conducive to focused work for Alex.

places.address: 153 Remsen St, Brooklyn, NY 11201, USA

reviews.text: Light filled airy space with delicious drinks. Met a friend here to pick up hot bevvies before a walk on the promenade. Matcha with light rose syrup was just right, and the venue was too.
reviews.author: Bridget Harvey Team

reviews.text:
Great coffee shop with some great coffee. A good variety of flavors and not too expensive. Staff is helpful and friendly. The latte was very tasty. Give them a try!

Edit* had different flavors like the ube and sesame but they had not been good the last few times. Tastes burned honestly or just never real flavor.
reviews.author: Juan Chavez

reviews.text: Cozy spot with a great atmosphere. Staffs are friendly and recommended us to try the strawberry matcha latte. 10/10 would come back.
reviews.author: jack cheng

personalization.forUser: The focus on coffee quality at Absolute Coffee may provide a stimulating environment for work for Alex.

places.address: 327 Atlantic Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11201, USA

reviews.text: I traveled to downtown brooklyn from flatbush looking for cafés that I'd like here, this is my first time being a customer in this café and I ordered a lavender latte, its pretty good, would visit this cafe again sometime. The staff and vibe here is really welcoming and genuine.
reviews.author: idiosyncratic kitty

reviews.text: Had a late with a croissant to start the day and it definitely hit the spot
reviews.author: charlene buytendag

reviews.text: Great coffee shop.  The he staff was friendly and gave me some recommendations. I had a latte and it was pretty tasty haven’t tried anything else yet but seems similar to other coffee spots. Nothing stands out but nothing bad either.
reviews.author: Juan Chavez

personalization.forUser: Nyla Café's atmosphere may appeal to Alex given their preferences.

places.address: 362 Hewes St, Brooklyn, NY 11211, USA

reviews.text: Great service, had the pesto eggs and salmon as recommended by the barista and it was delicious!! The barista also made me a special drink for my birthday. Also super delicious. The place gives calm, cozy vibes. I’d def drop back in, the next time I’m in the area.
reviews.author: Sky Britnei

reviews.text: So, I know there are tons of coffee shops in NYC, but I found Nyla Cafe, and honestly, it's way more than just a coffee shop. It felt super cozy, like being at home. And obviously, the coffee is fresh and delicious! Yair, the barista there, is seriously the best with his amazing service and super friendly vibe. I'm definitely going back next time and telling all my friends about it.
reviews.author: Zohar Kimhi

reviews.text: Super cute little cafe, excellent coffee from Devoción and absolutely delicious French-inspired food. Scratch-made spinach and cheese quiche was superb, and the potatoes au gratin were delightfully rich. Relaxed atmosphere, good service.
reviews.author: Niko Villani-Fragákis

query: romantic dinner spots in the West Village

personalization.forUser: While not Italian, Japanese, or Mexican, the romantic ambiance might appeal to Alex, and the menu could offer options aligning with their broader taste.

places.address: 38 Commerce St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: Wild Cherry brings Old Hollywood elegance to the West Village. The service is impeccable, the cocktails are thoughtfully crafted, and the food is both high quality and delicious. We ordered the oysters, the Frog Legs Kiev, and the steak dinner for two. Every dish was exceptional, with the Frog Legs Kiev being my personal favorite. I would highly recommend Wild Cherry to anyone who appreciates excellent food, a sense of theatre, and a genuinely fun night out.
reviews.author: Evan Martinez

reviews.text:
Diner aesthetic meets French cuisine is an intriguing twist, but not necessarily needed. The ambiance, though charming, felt at times like a Times Square attraction. The curved ceiling and thin walls amplified sound, making it difficult to hear the one you were dining with.

Service was fine, attentive, but not at the level you’d expect from the people behind Frenchette and Le Veau d’or. It was clear it was all hands on deck, but that left the bathroom a mess and missed opportunities for real hospitality.

The food was priced somewhat high for what it was — it lacked the richness French cuisine should have but the menu items did have the nostalgic comfort diner food brings. The Alfredo and rice and beans were charming!

What they did do right was the martini, but you can find many a good martini in Manhattan and with more intimate atmosphere and hospitable service.
reviews.author: Rach

reviews.text:
Took me three weeks to get a reservation and I was really happy with coming here despite inclement weather. Both hostess and the First Gentleman I spoke to Nicolas were very kind and helpful! I had to run in and out because I work but I had the coconut cake! It was delicious! I was at the bar though and I didn’t try the food but if I get another reservation I most definitely will try the menu!

Get loud though but it was party to the side of me liquor glasses all over the table..so there’s that. However, it was a nice little date for me to me and will be back especially for that cake.

Thank you!!

Leandra
reviews.author: Leandra Wilkerson

personalization.forUser: While the cuisine isn't specified as Italian, Japanese, or Mexican, the upscale atmosphere could be suitable for a romantic dinner that Alex might appreciate.

places.address: 314 W 11th St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: We cant say enough about how good the food was at the Golden Swan! It was gourmet' all the way! I had a specialty drink of danedlion lemonade, it was fantastic! From appetizers to main course to dessert, everything was exquisit and perfectly prepared!  The atmosphere was enchanting.  The chef, Doug Brixton, came out to talk with us about our food, he is definately an expert in his field!  His staff was wonderful and accomodating! I dont get to NYC often, but will definately eat here again and highly recommend the Golden Swan to those who want to enjoy an evening of fine dining in the heart of NYC
reviews.author: Mary Herman

reviews.text: Lovely restaurant in the West Village. Perfect for a "date" with your wife or anybody else and perfect on a snowy Saturday. Our brunch pancakes were superb, fluffy and delicious. Romantic decor and super friendly service (calling out Isabelle).
reviews.author: Nils Paellmann

reviews.text: Such an amazing experience! Love the variety of service options; Bar and Casual Dining or upstairs Formal Dining (where we were). There is even a special area on the top level that for up to 12 guests for special occasions. The food is unreal and has so much detail put in the the flavors of each entree. From the appetizers to the dessert they are something we will never forget and will come in town to come back to eat again. The chef has done a fabulous job with the menu and the ambience of the entire experience.
reviews.author: Adreamgrl41

personalization.forUser: Though not specifically aligning with Alex's preferred cuisines, its intimate setting could make it a good option if they are open to trying something new.

places.address: 90 Bedford St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: Little Owl was established in 2006. I have had this restaurant in my radar for many years but it took me 19 years to finally dine here. I wish I discovered this gem of a restaurant sooner. The vibe is of a comfy cozy neighborhood restaurant. We enjoyed the French onion soup, meatball sliders and the Bibb and Beets salad. The salad was absolutely delicious and worth coming back for that dish alone. I enjoyed my non-alcoholic drink but found the desserts a tad too sweet for my taste. The service was excellent. Jorge was especially hospitable and made us feel welcomed. I will be back soon.
reviews.author: Susan Seto

reviews.text: I had an incredible experience at Little Owl. Suggested to me by a friend‘s mother. It did not disappoint. If you’re going, definitely get the halibut. A very unique yet simple way of cooking the fish. The story goes that it used to be grilled until the grill went out in the first week and they’ve decided to broil ever since. They really go over and above to make sure you’re comfortable as well. It was very nice to feel well taken care of.
reviews.author: Hannah Clark

reviews.text: Little Owl — tucked right under the iconic "Friends" apartment building — is a must-stop in the West Village. Cozy, welcoming, and absolutely delicious. The meatball is non-negotiable: tender, perfectly seasoned, and sauced just right. Service is friendly, the vibe is intimate, and every plate feels thoughtfully made. Come hungry, order the meatball first, and grab a quick photo outside afterward. Perfect NYC spot!
reviews.author: M M

personalization.forUser: As an Italian restaurant, Cotenna directly aligns with Alex's stated preference for Italian cuisine, making it a potentially excellent choice.

places.address: 21 Bedford St # A, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: Great spot and atmosphere. You get decent food and nice servings. I would avoid the red wine selection by the glass, they very kindly replaced a glass I didn’t like with another wine while I did not say anything it was just as bad. (Valpolicella and Super Tuscan) the white was decent Vermoentino)
reviews.author: Ziad Iskandar

reviews.text:
Cotenna was an outstanding dining experience from start to finish. The atmosphere is warm, inviting, and effortlessly elegant—perfect for both a special night out or a relaxed, elevated dinner.

Our waiter, Alex, truly made the evening exceptional. He was attentive, knowledgeable, and struck the perfect balance between professional and personable. His recommendations were spot-on, and he made us feel genuinely taken care of throughout the meal.

The food was phenomenal. The lamb chops were cooked to perfection—tender, flavorful, and beautifully seasoned. The ravioli was equally impressive: rich, delicate, and bursting with flavor, clearly made with incredible attention to detail and quality ingredients.

Every element of the experience—from the service to the cuisine—was top tier. Cotenna is a place that delivers consistently and thoughtfully, and I can’t wait to return. Highly recommend.
reviews.author: Cheryl Doustan

reviews.text: The food was so good. We ordered Grilled Octopus salad, Bucatini with pesto, sun dried tomatoes and burrata cheese and branzino with lemon sauce and all of them were on point. Portion size was good. The service was excellent. The noise level was a little high inside. So we opted for eating outside and then there was lots of traffic. And they had no coffee or tea. Otherwise it was excellent.
reviews.author: Seiko Rosen

personalization.forUser: As an Italian restaurant, Pesce Pasta directly aligns with Alex's stated preference for Italian cuisine, making it a potentially excellent choice.

places.address: 262 Bleecker St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text:
We’ve been wanting to try this place and finally did! Pasta was tasty and seafood were cooked perfect.
There were some tout groups at the restaurant.
reviews.author: Amy Kang

reviews.text: Best Italian food we had in our one week stay in New York. This location is authentic and charming. We are lucky that the pizza place down the street had a line an hour long. This was the better choice for us. Great choices on the menu, and everything was delicious. Don’t miss out on the experience. We ate with a few other locals who seem to visit often. Service is outstanding!
reviews.author: Mackenzie McHale

reviews.text: On a busy Bleecker Street, in the heart of West Village, I walked into this typical Italian trattoria which serves exelent seafood, pasta and fresh salads. No reservations were needed.
reviews.author: Svetlana J. Cemin

personalization.forUser: Although the cuisine isn't Italian, Japanese, or Mexican, the sophisticated atmosphere may appeal to Alex, depending on their mood.

places.address: 99 Bank St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: A lovely west village brunch spot offering good variety of more than typical brunch items. The place was pretty packed by the time our mains came out. Lovely location with lots of sunlight and good service, other diners enhanced the atmosphere as well.
reviews.author: Jia Sun

reviews.text: Party of 3 had a reservation for 6:30pm on a Sunday evening in October. We had the crudo and burrata to share for the table. I had the sauteed salmon entree and it was pretty delicious. The server recommended the Perpetual Jam cocktail which was a good choice. Total including tips came to around 80-90 bucks per person. The ambience is great. It's a neat and quiet place, but the quantity of food I thought was low, for the price. Especially the crudo plate hardly had anything. They have a large clean restroom in the back. The staff are all very warm and friendly.
reviews.author: Vipul Singh

reviews.text: Great food, ambiance and staff. I had a reservation for Friday night that I made week of. I was seated immediately. The staff were very friendly and helpful, they kept refilling my water. The swordfish was super hot. Loved the flavors, the risotto was perfect. Highly recommend if you are in the area.
reviews.author: Amelia T

personalization.forUser: As an Italian restaurant, L'Artusi perfectly matches Alex's preference for Italian cuisine, offering a high-quality dining experience.

places.address: 228 W 10th St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: Had L’Artusi on my list to try — it’s a must! Grabbed a reservation for 2 @ the bar on a Friday at 12:15 for 12:45pm. The garganelli pasta was incredible - I was hesitant about the mushroom ragu but it was so delicious and perfectly done. The olive oil cake was my favorite thing we ate — unbelievable flavor. A spoonful of cake w / the raisin marmelleta and mousse was absolute perfection. Highly recommend L’Artusi. Spent $150 including tip for 2 people - no alcohol.
reviews.author: Kristina I

reviews.text:
Awesome experience. The roasted mushrooms were not what we were expecting, in a GOOD Way. They were fantastic. The Pici 'Cacio e Pepe' was good as well, I just didn't eat my much because I wanted more pork chop, read below.

We got the pork chop as our main course. It has to be one of the best pork chops I've ever had. I would order it again in a heartbeat!
reviews.author: Ty Ansley

reviews.text: Absolutely amazing experience at L’Artusi! The Cacio e Pepe was excellent—perfectly creamy with just the right amount of pepper. The Garganelli was equally delicious, rich, and great if you like a more tomato-based rich flavor. Olive oil cake was unique, but not as good as expected. Beautiful ambiance, great service, and truly outstanding food. Highly recommend!
reviews.author: Salem A

personalization.forUser: As an Italian restaurant, Palma directly aligns with Alex's stated preference for Italian cuisine, making it a potentially excellent choice.

places.address: 28 Cornelia St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: This was undoubtedly one of the best Italian meals I’ve had since living in NYC! Highly recommend the carciofi fritti (fried calamari), arancini (risotto balls), ravioli Cacio e Pepe (very rich) and Candele Spezzate alla Genovese with GF pene (INCREDIBLE)!!! The La Vie en Rose cocktail was refreshing and the Brunello was delicious. The atmosphere at lunchtime was lovely and the staff were are super friendly. I cannot wait to come back to this restaurant and try everything! The menu was clearly labeled for gluten free, vegetarian and vegan options. Staff was able to easily accommodate allergies to gluten, nuts, coconut and sesame.
reviews.author: Elizabeth Sara Ross

reviews.text: Such a beautifully decorated and charming restaurant serving some of the best Italian cuisine I have ever had! Their homemade pastas were incredibly executed, and the flavors were out of this world. The Focaccia and olive oil came out warm and perfectly toasted. The risotto was truly life changing and an absolute must try. Highly recommend dining in the covered outdoor patio as the atmosphere was wonderful. Palma has easily become one of my favorites of all time! Would come back again and again as this place is a destination in itself.
reviews.author: Mel D

reviews.text:
We finally made it to Palma and everything was fantastic. It was the day after Christmas and it was snowing so it was quieter than usual according to the bartender, Kacey. She was fantastic and made perfect recommendations.

We had the focaccia, Tuna Tartare, octopus, meatballs, and Candele Spezzate alla Genovese. Everything was delicious, perfectly balanced and seasoned especially the Candele which we were told is seasonal so it will be off the menu by spring. Go get it!!

We finished with one the best tiramisus we’ve ever had.
reviews.author: Justin Cohen

personalization.forUser: While not Italian, Japanese, or Mexican, the restaurant may have options that appeal to Alex's broader tastes or be a place to try something new.

places.address: 447 Hudson St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: Brunch or dinner is always incredible!! The chefs seasonal menu’s are first class. Beautiful patio seating outside, or the chef counter inside to watch the magic happen. Classy interior is comfortable any time year and the marble bar is well stocked and first come first serve! There’s also a private wine cellar for larger groups!
reviews.author: Boz Kramer

reviews.text: A quintessential brunch spot with good food and lovely atmosphere. Delicious arugula salad, phenomenal duck hash, and a dark chocolate bread pudding that smoulders in its tastiness. You definitely should visit.
reviews.author: Farid Hamka

reviews.text:
Overpriced inconsistent food with a few standout dishes, good service, unbearably loud indoor space with terrible acoustics.

I came here with a few friends and we ordered a variety of apps and sides to share, multiple rounds of drinks, and entrees. Of the food, the sweet potatoes, fried artichokes, and burrata were exceptional. Everything else was pretty bad. My steak, which I ordered rare, was tough and cooked medium well so it was barely edible. My pot of chocolate was very gritty.

My friends enjoyed the scallops and gnocchi but I didn't enjoy my entree or dessert at all.

Great attentive service.

The worst part was how insanely loud the place is with no dampening so it was like being in a noise conversation tunnel all night. Probably the outside seating is better.

Overall, the food and drinks are a bit overpriced for the iffy quality. We spent over $500 for 4 people.
reviews.author: Yiyi Zhang

personalization.forUser: While the cuisine isn't specified as Italian, Japanese, or Mexican, the ambiance might appeal to Alex, and the menu could offer options aligning with their broader taste.

places.address: 86 Bedford St, New York, NY 10014, USA

reviews.text: Everything about this is NYC. No sign on the door and it looks a like an if you know you know kinda place from the outside. Stepping inside is old school vibes with art deco. A real fireplace really set the ambiance. To go with the cool vibes is some great food. Everything we had was fantastic. Some really unique items on the menu that are executed flawlessly like the French onion croquettes, cheesesteak and all the desserts. Would definitely recommend.
reviews.author: KC

reviews.text: Nothing about this restaurant was anything short of 5 stars. We sat at the bar and Shawn the bartender was attentive and knowledgeable. The oysters were fresh with a delicious mignonette. The Delmonico steak had a perfect char. The Caesar salad croutons were warm and crisp with a soft inside. Unlike any Caesar I’ve ever had. The drinks were curated to our taste and adapted beautifully. History and ambiance are unmatched. All the staff were warm and professional. We took a risk as walk ins without a reservation and it paid off.
reviews.author: Peter Gibbons

reviews.text: One of the best dinners we have had in a long time. Don greeted us at the door and Francesco took good care of us at the bar. The pasta dish was a standout that I’m happy we ordered. But you have to come for the cheese steak and the strip. 10/10 meal and really nice ambiance inside. Amazing addition from the Catch team.
reviews.author: Tyler Heffernan

personalization.forUser: Sushi Azabu is a good choice for Alex because it offers Japanese cuisine, which is one of Alex's favorite cuisines.

places.address: 428 Greenwich St, New York, NY 10013, USA

reviews.text: Top-notch Japanese quality at a reasonable price. The atmosphere and taste were exceptional, especially the six-piece sushi set, which was outstanding. As a nice touch, Shota and his team served us hot green tea at the end. Highly recommend!
reviews.author: Kohei

reviews.text:
One word to describe this establishment-inconsistent.
I have visited Azabu 4 times and ordered delivery once,which of course would deem my rating as precise as one can get.
It is such a shame, because I sincerely enjoy this restaurant and would even give it a high 4 star on days the Head chef is working. On days he is not available or on vacation it is an absolute disaster service wise and the food is almost a 2 star rating. Everything is Chewy, pale, horribly cut. When he is available everything is pristine. Buttery, fresh, delicious. Take a look at my depressing 150$ delivery order. My Otoro looks like it’s a phantom of yesterday’s Tuna. Better to close your restaurant on days the head chef isn’t available then keep open and lose clients.
reviews.author: Donia Aduna

reviews.text:
Loved it! Multiple Omakase menus to choose from. Intimate wooden interior. Definitely prefer the counter for two diners however a table for three or more is recommended.
Denshin Yuki was chosen for us by the manager and exquisite. Still going strong after so many years. Definitely on the end of the scale but worth it.
reviews.author: Chris M

personalization.forUser: Tetsu is a good choice for Alex because it offers Japanese cuisine, which is one of Alex's favorite cuisines.

places.address: 78 Leonard St, New York, NY 10013, USA

reviews.text:
Fantastic experience. It was a journey of unexpected flavors. It’s exceptional to be able to enjoy Masa’s mastery in this outstanding location. There are so many different nooks and crannies in this place. The two Michelin stars are well deserved.

If you go make a point of visiting the downstairs space where you see how the same amount of space is allocated to the guests as to the kitchen.

The chefs were very friendly and took the time to explain and enlighten.
reviews.author: Ziad Iskandar

reviews.text: One of the best burgers in the city, genuinely. The blend of sushi and then burger is a wonderful combination and should be adopted in other places. The bar is a great place to sit because you can watch the food being made. The sushi is amazing of course.
reviews.author: Omar Aly

reviews.text: Beautiful restaurant by chef mass in TriBeCa. Close to the canal st subway stations. They have big windows that open up and there are tables inside next to them - snatch one if you can! (No outdoor seating). Great bar with creative cocktails and nice sake and wine. They have an amazing happy hour menu including $5 fried chicken and $8 sparkling rose. There’s a yuzu cake with yuzu cream and grilled peaches that’s delicious!
reviews.author: W Gmail

personalization.forUser: Brushstroke is a good choice for Alex because it offers Japanese cuisine, which is one of Alex's favorite cuisines.

places.address: 30 Hudson St, New York, NY 10013, USA

reviews.text: Having eaten many tonkotsu ramens around the city, I was curious about the creativity behind the Bouley team and opted for a different noodle soup. The broth is a thick and creamy concoction of soymilk and white miso that pairs well with the thick udon (thick flat strands like fettucine). The lobster claw is perfectly poached, and the side of nori to garnish adds another layer of umami. The 8-seater around the bar adds to an intimate feel within the beautiful and tranquil setting!
reviews.author: Andy Ng

reviews.text:
Allegedly "underground" and "little-known," this is attached to Brushstroke in the spot that used to be a similarly incredible sushi-bar.

It transformed into an excellent ramen shop, specializing in tonkotsu broth ramen (but others are available).
reviews.author: Jerry Levine

reviews.text:
If you're into bourgeois places, then it's a great start. If not, be open minded and look pass the bourgeoisness. This place is legit. Trust me, I'm Asian. I know my ramen.
For the food, I had the wagyu garlic gyoza and it was fantastic. It taste like a high class burger in a gyoza wrap. Its fantastic. Try it. The sauce was some kind of ponzu sauce. Strong citrus flavor. If you know what calamansi is, that's what will remind you of. Its not overpowering and dip it with th bitterness of the mustard and it's a great compliment to th flavors. Not quite a flavor explosion of grilled wagyu but great none the less.
The tonkotsu ramen is worth going back for. Thick tonkotsu broth, chasu that just falls off, noodles that are firm yet melts slightly in your mouth. A fried chopped garlic and chili sauce are great with it as well but I encourage you to take it in as is and have chili little by little by making a little ramen on your spoon. This place is worth it. Go.
Oishi kata.
reviews.author: Fulbert Cue

personalization.forUser: Ichimura at Uchu is a good choice for Alex because it offers Japanese cuisine, which is one of Alex's favorite cuisines.

places.address: 412 Greenwich St, New York, NY 10013, USA

reviews.text:
Pretty incredible place and despite the very high price actually worth it.  Just an incredible experience all around - several dishes were “first ever” and the quality of everything was just incredible.  Watching a master sushi chef at work is half the experience, the rest is his delicious food, particularly the “appetizers” leading up to the sushi.  Very large pieces of Hokkaido uni with caviar, an incredible conch dish, an amazing noodle and hairy crab item.  Sushi pieces are very large and generous. Amazing selections of wine and drinks and a nice double magnum of d’Yquem that went great with the tuna.  Please go you won’t regret it.

Slight ding on the service for one server who was slightly annoying but overall great service from the team.
reviews.author: Richard S

reviews.text: Had an amazing time celebrating my birthday at one of my favorite sushi chef’s restaurants! The sushi was meticulously prepared and absolutely perfect, as always. It’s such a pleasure dining here every time. Highly recommend for anyone who appreciates top-notch sushi and a great experience!
reviews.author: PACSSU

reviews.text: Spectacular. The best omakase I’ve had in NYC. Thank you to the team for an unforgettable night. Every course was delicious, and the service was second to none. The fatty tuna + desert wine pairing will transport you into another dimension.
reviews.author: Benjamin Zelditch

personalization.forUser: Shiki Omakase is a good choice for Alex because it offers Japanese cuisine, which is one of Alex's favorite cuisines.

places.address: 71 W Houston St, New York, NY 10012, USA

reviews.text:
Nice little omakase restaurant, very good service. Food was fresh, raw fish was room temperature, all servings made before your eyes. Otoro was the best but their specials like Winter and Summer creations were really good, $18 each.
Had the 17 pieces omakase. Menu was standard and the items were decent. Serving size of the sushi pieces varied from small to regular.
Not much conversation or interaction with the chefs as they were quiet and busy making the foods. I had better omakase experience with chefs.
Decent prices for the amount of food.
reviews.author: Peter Yong (PedroJoven)

reviews.text:
Great quality, flavorful, and very well done omakase at a reasonable price. Had the 17 course menu for $100 at lunch time. They also offer a 12 course menu for $65. Both menus offer a good variety of fish and flavor combinations. The courses are definitely more classic and traditional but well done and tasty.

The interior is small; feels like proper Japan. But it’s a comfortable noise level — some quiet background music, which makes it easy to talk.

The omakase chefs don’t really explain much about the food — they just name the fish and dish when they serve you. You can see how they prepare everything right in front of you. The pace of the courses are good. Nice attention to detail from the chefs: I’ve been here twice and both times when the chef noticed that I was left-handed, they placed the food at the different side of the plate.

Service is attentive and quick.
The second time I was here, we were celebrating my sister’s birthday. At the end, they dimmed the lights, switched from their mellow instrumental  background music to 50 Cents - In Da Club playing on high volume, gave my sister a sparkler, and served her another sushi course with a candle, and the entire team danced to the song for about 30 seconds. Best birthday recognition I’ve ever seen from a restaurant staff.
reviews.author: Jasmin

reviews.text: Was able to snag a resy at this place very last minute (I think day of) for the last 3 seats at the bar at the last serving time they had on a Saturday night. The way this meal changed my entire mood in a short 90 minute seating. This was some of the best omakase I have had in the city and for the best price I've been able to find. The fish was fresher than could be and every single course was delectable and yummy. I left actually feeling pretty full (which can be tough at omakase experiences sometimes) and throughly enjoyed the entire dining experience. Even though we were the last ones at the bar, they never rushed us and made our time together really special. Would love to bring a big group and take over the entire sushi bar, it was that good!!!
reviews.author: Josh Rose

personalization.forUser: Blue Ribbon Sushi is a good choice for Alex because it offers Japanese cuisine, which is one of Alex's favorite cuisines.

places.address: 119 Sullivan St, New York, NY 10012, USA

reviews.text: Great sushi restaurant. I enjoy the pickled vegetable plate. the eggplant was a delight. the escarole had a lot of depth of flavor. The spinach in sesame was a starter I'd go back for again. It is pricey, however the sushi and sashimi are of great quality and are well crafted. The atmosphere is great. Compact and lively.
reviews.author: carlos borges

reviews.text:
I came to Blue Ribbon Sushi about two years ago and had an amazing experience — a big sushi platter that cost around $200 and felt well worth it. I recently went back for a quick date night, and while the food was still good, the prices have gotten insanely high. I know inflation is real, but this felt pretty extreme.

We ordered the crispy rice with spicy tuna, the Hamachi Serrano, two pieces of otoro sushi, the Unadon, plus one basic bottle of hot sake. The total came out to about $180 including tip, which honestly blew my mind given how little food we actually got.

The otoro sushi especially was disappointing — each piece was around $18, and the slice of fish on top was tiny. It didn’t taste bad, but for that price, I expected something more memorable. Overall, the food was decent but definitely not worth what we paid — and I left still feeling hungry.

On the positive side, the service was excellent. The staff was super attentive and managed to seat us last minute even though the place was fully booked. The restaurant itself is small, cozy, and great for a date night, but I’d just say be prepared to spend a lot more than you’d expect.

In short, the food is fine, the vibe is nice, but the prices are over the top for what you get. I wouldn’t recommend it for a casual dinner unless you’re ready to splurge.
reviews.author: Chloe

reviews.text:
I just left Blue Ribbon Sushi NYC completely disappointed — and still hungry. I paid $57 for food that wasn’t worth half of it. The menu is confusing, with no clear prices, and shrimp tempura wasn’t even listed. When it came, it was just four tiny pieces for $18 — bland, forgettable, and definitely not fresh.

But the worst part was the rude service. I politely asked the waiter if I could charge my phone, and he disappeared. When he finally came back, instead of being helpful, he said, “So, are you ordering more or not?”
That attitude alone ruined the experience. No warmth, no hospitality — just a feeling that I was an inconvenience for not ordering fast enough.

I only went there because Sushi Lin across the street doesn’t have a full kitchen at this location — I really wish they did. I would have had a better meal and much better service.

Overall: Overpriced sushi, unfriendly staff, terrible customer service, and poor value.
If you’re in NYC and want good sushi, skip Blue Ribbon Sushi — there are far better options nearby that actually care about their customers.
reviews.author: Elnaz E

personalization.forUser: Nobu Downtown is a good choice for Alex because it offers Japanese cuisine, which is one of Alex's favorite cuisines.

places.address: 195 Broadway, New York, NY 10007, USA

reviews.text:
I rarely write negative reviews, but this experience was a letdown from start to finish. Despite having a reservation, we were forced to wait 20 minutes while the reception staff treated us with arrogance and dismissal.
The dining area is in the basement; it was incredibly loud, stuffy, and poorly ventilated. It felt suffocating rather than high-end.

The Food:
We were a table of four and spent $550, yet left completely unsatisfied. Most hot dishes were oily, heavy on seasoning, or lacked quality.

• Glacier 51 Sea Bass ($56): Supposed to be truffle and miso, but had zero flavor of either.
• A5 Wagyu New Style: A waste of premium meat. It tasted overwhelmingly of generic soy sauce.
• Squid Pasta: Essentially just wok-fried vegetables with squid. I’d expect this at a casual Chinese restaurant, not here.
• Shiitake Salad ($30): Way too oily.
• Miso Soup ($9): Tasted exactly like instant soup.
• Salmon Tartare: Heavily over-seasoned and the portion size was pathetic.
• New Style White Fish: The flavor profile was just weird.
• Grilled Salmon ($40): Oily and unremarkable.
• Sushi: The nigiri ($8/piece) was average at best. The Salmon Tacos were too salty, though the Lobster Tacos were passable.

The Service:
The service was as poor as the food. Haha when I left a standard 15% tip, he sneered at me.

If you are looking for authentic Japanese food or a pleasant environment, go elsewhere. Nobu worldwide seems to be resting on its name rather than quality. Don't go.
reviews.author: Gigi Wu

reviews.text: Over the weekend (Sunday) I was taken here for my birthday. Restaurant wasn't busy, so it was a quiet evening. It was our 1st time. Our server Sigar (apologies if I spelled that wrong) went over the menu with us & helped us choose. Our drinks, the crispy rice, black cod, doughnuts & everything else we ordered was very good. Our waiter was attentive and very nice to us. I plan to go back soon.
reviews.author: L C

reviews.text: My experience at Nobu Downtown was absolutely amazing. The service was impeccable—attentive, professional, and perfectly timed. I tried the tasting menu, and it was truly worth it. Every dish was beautifully presented and bursting with flavor. From start to finish, everything was delicious. Highly recommend for a special night out in New York!
reviews.author: Bruno Rangel

personalization.forUser: Noda is a good choice for Alex because it offers Japanese cuisine, which is one of Alex's favorite cuisines.

places.address: 37 W 20th St, New York, NY 10011, USA

reviews.text:
I chose this place for my husband's birthday dinner, and the entrance alone set the tone. Walking into the secret space and waiting for the curtain to drop felt like the start of a show!
Every single dish was delicious. I’m usually a huge Uni lover, but the other courses here were so outstanding that they stole the show. My personal favorite of the night was definitely the Unagi absolutely amazing.
The service was truly next-level. Both the manager and the chef were incredibly attentive and observant; they anticipated our needs without being intrusive. As introverts, we really appreciated how they balanced friendly small talk with giving us space. They really knew how to "read the room" perfectly.
A few minor notes: Even though I mentioned it was a birthday celebration, there wasn't a special dessert dish or candle. They did offer a celebratory shot at the end, but since we don't drink alcohol, we missed out on that.
Regarding drinks, I had read other reviews mentioning a potential push for alcohol orders (since there are no add-on options), but we didn't feel that pressure at all. As soon as we ordered soft drinks, they immediately took the hint and didn't force anything on us, which we appreciated.
Overall, I highly recommend this spot for a delicious Omakase meal and a unique vibe, rather than strictly for a special "event."
reviews.author: 이까꿍

reviews.text: No words! We went last night and the whole experience start to finish was an exceptional experience. From the ambiance, the service, the professionalism and quality of food… and sake lol. One of the best omakase experiences I’ve had. And the best in NYC hands down. Can’t wait to go back!! Shout out Tim, chef Noda & Jimmy! You guys are incredible!
reviews.author: Sara Mezzacappa

reviews.text:
This is such a special place — you're in for a treat! We've been coming here for our anniversary for the past two years and it's wow'd us each time. There are only two seatings a day and 8 seats in the entire restaurant, so a very intimate experience. The chef and staff are chatting with you the whole time and are so knowledgeable and talented. They often research their guests as well — they knew all about my partner's work and running hobby. (I guess I was harder to find info on!)

The food (as well as sake/wine pairing, which I highly recommend) is SUCH an experience. The best sushi I've had, hands down. Everything is presented so beautifully as well — each new sake and/or wine is brought in a new gorgeous glass.

This is always at the top of my recommendation list for friends and family seeking the right spot to celebrate a special occasion.
reviews.author: Loren

personalization.forUser: Zutto Japanese American Pub is a good choice for Alex because it offers Japanese cuisine, which is one of Alex's favorite cuisines.

places.address: 77 Hudson St, New York, NY 10013, USA

reviews.text:
Zutto is the kind of spot you come with friends and end up staying all night. Fun drinks, a beautifully loaded sushi boat made for sharing, and steaming bowls of ramen that bring it all together. Casual, cozy, and full of flavor. The sushi boat is customizable. You can choose any sushi rolls from their large variety of sushi. Definitely worth it!

Follow me @foodie.elite on IG and Tiktok for more!
reviews.author: Foodie Elite

reviews.text: Zutto in Tribeca is one of those laidback chill type Japanese restaurant that offers Japanese street-style food to omakase. Step inside and you will notice the amazing crowd with laughters and excitement in a cozy setting. Not only does Zutto have Japanese sake, whisky, and beer but their handcrafted cocktails is definitely not to be missed. Their sushi boats is a spectacular deal for an entire party or whole entire group! Fill it up with your favorites and it will arrive on a boat that mesmerizes everyone. Each dish and piece is full of umami with freshness and quality you can taste. If you’re looking for a Japanese spot that’s tasty, fresh, and full of vibes, Zutto is the place you need to check out.
reviews.author: itzelenaho

reviews.text:
Absolutely delicious! The spicy miso ramen is out of this world — rich, flavorful, and perfectly balanced. Sushi was super fresh and tasty. Great selection of Japanese snacks and sides, plus affordable and solid beer options.

Zutto hits the sweet spot between quality and price — definitely one of the best value spots around. Highly recommended for a laid-back yet authentic Japanese-American dining experience!
reviews.author: Artur St

personalization.forUser: O Ya is a good choice for Alex because it offers Japanese cuisine, which is one of Alex's favorite cuisines.

places.address: 75 Barclay St, New York, NY 10007, USA

reviews.text:
One of the best omakase experiences I’ve ever had! I came in with very high expectations after dining at Ito in Las Vegas at the Fontainebleau Hotel—which was phenomenal—and I was excited to see they had a location in NYC. I’m happy to say this experience exceeded my expectations.

From the moment we arrived, the staff was warm, welcoming, attentive, and prompt. We had the honor of meeting Chef Kevin, who was incredibly gracious and truly an artist in his craft. Every course showcased the highest quality ingredients, with a burst of flavor in every bite. From the appetizers to dessert, each dish was beautifully presented and thoughtfully crafted.

I especially loved that we were given the option to add additional pieces at the end of the course, and that Chef Kevin offered this before dessert—it was a thoughtful touch that elevated the entire experience. The drink menu is also very well curated, with an excellent selection of sake and other alcoholic beverages to complement the meal.

This is absolutely a place I will continue to visit every time I’m in town. A must-try for any omakase lover in NYC.
reviews.author: Lideyni Flores

reviews.text: Very delicious meal with quality fish. The cod was soft and paired nicely with the miso. The standouts for me were the truffle mushroom soup which was just nice on a cold day and the mushroom tasted so fresh. The seared otoro had a smokey flavor to it and melted in my mouth. The truffle Wagyu was definitely my favorite because what’s not to love?? Truffle was strong and freshly shaved. Wagyu torched to the perfect fatty level. The dessert was very lovely liked the buttery cream on top with the crunchy popcorn and miso base. The counter does get quite crowded and seats more than the typical amount of people at an omakase
reviews.author: Michelle Lin

reviews.text: We have dined at multiple Michelin rated restaurants around the world and can honestly say that this was the best dining experience that we've ever had. From the start, the concept of only opening the doors 5 minutes before seating allows you and the rest of the patrons to gather outside in anticipation, it's a nice way to meet everyone you'll be dining with before sitting down. Once the doors opened they immediately checked us in, took our coats and commented on the reservation notes, wishing me a happy birthday. I was again wished a happy birthday as I was being seated and then a third time by our Omakase chef. The food was incredible and the staff was so friendly. Important note: if you don't like group dining experiences, this is not for you. If you like sitting with and meeting new people with delicious food and attentive service, this experience is well worth the money. While it seems that some reviews comment that they didn't like the food, I am getting the impression that at last parts of the menu change, for example we had a mushroom and truffle soup whereas others mention a miso soup. The rice for the nigiri was warm and fresh, and wasabi was grated right in front of us before being added to our food. Will recommend to everyone I know!
reviews.author: Kacie

issues: Personalization could be stronger by explicitly mentioning the trendy vibe for each result, as this is a key aspect of the query.
Some personalization notes are somewhat generic, such as 'might appeal to Alex's adventurous side' without specific details.

personalization.forUser: While not matching Alex's preferred cuisines directly, Isla & Co. offers a globally-inspired menu that might have some items aligning with their adventurous palate.

places.address: 66 Grand St, Brooklyn, NY 11249, USA

reviews.text: I am looking forward to coming back. The food and drinks have been exceptional. Our waiter was so attentive and the service is super fast. We sampled everything from the whipped feta, peppers, broccolini, kangaroo bites, truffle Mac and cheese, lamb ratatouille, espresso martini flight. There wasnt any dish nor beverage that we didnt like. Looking fwd to returning.
reviews.author: Kathina M.

reviews.text:
Everything we ordered was excellent. Start with the espresso flight and don’t skip the appetizers, the whipped ricotta was rich and creamy, the shishito peppers had the perfect balance of char and heat, and the kangaroo skewers were surprisingly delicious, with flavors that blended beautifully and didn’t feel gimmicky at all.

If you’re into bold, smoky, saucy dishes, the lamb rigatoni is a must. The ambiance really seals the deal: stylish, energetic, and ideal for catching up with friends without feeling rushed.

The cocktails were thoughtfully crafted. The Smoke Show especially stands out if you enjoy a spicy drink.

Overall, a standout experience. Highly recommend, and I’ll absolutely be back.
reviews.author: Ariel Montrose

reviews.text: Really nice food! The staff are so nice and the vibe is great. My only issue was charging $2 extra for the GF bun on the breakfast role when they swapped the fries for a salad and didn’t include the hash browns, without even flagging that when ordered. I am celiac, so I’m glad they were taken out - but taking the hash browns and fries off to sub for a salad and charging $2 is a little unnecessary. But, other than this minor detail it’s a definite go to spot for sure!
reviews.author: Padraig Henry

personalization.forUser: Although French, Le Crocodile's high-quality ingredients and sophisticated atmosphere might appeal to Alex's appreciation for fine dining experiences.

places.address: 80 Wythe Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11249, USA

reviews.text: Really good food, with the highlights being the mushroom pate and the duck confit. Service was top notch and I loved the dessert. Great place for a date, book club meeting, or business meeting based on the people around us. The menu changes seasonally so the stuff we got might not be what you get. The restaurant is wheelchair accessible.
reviews.author: Nikko Ong

reviews.text:
Very cute French spot, love the decor.
Bar seats suit for low number parties, also comfortable seats for party of more.
I had the burger and it was great, love the brioche bun, patty was well cooked and juicy, very guilty pleasure (for me)
Banana pudding taste like a very moist banana bread (I guess that’s what a pudding supposed to taste like 🤣🤣)
The profiteroles were delicious as well!
Great place for couples and friends.
reviews.author: Samantha Yuan

reviews.text: Le Crocodile was fantastic. I wasn’t sure what to expect but I pleasantly surprised with how good the food was. The menu is unique. I tried certain dishes I’ve never had before like steak tartare & mushroom pate. Both were incredible. Entree I got the bistro steak frites, it was good not great but tried the roast chicken from my friend it was delicious. My other friends got the duck breast and really liked it. The sticky banana date pudding was so good didn’t last more than 30 seconds on our table hahah. Will definitely be returning to this spot! Great place for a date or dinner with friends
reviews.author: Arman Habib

personalization.forUser: Gertie offers a classic brunch experience, which could be a good option for Alex if they're looking for a familiar and reliable choice.

places.address: 357 Grand St, Brooklyn, NY 11211, USA

reviews.text: Great experience all around. Delicious food and a great Saturday Brunch vibe. Took the Matzo Ball Soup and Smash-burger despite coming for brunch and didn’t disappoint. Only negative is they’re moving closer to their Sister location “Gertrud’s” in Park Slope in a month.
reviews.author: Zack Glassman

reviews.text:
*Sept 2024 update*

Just had my bridal shower here and it was the best event ever! The back patio area was perfect for our group and since it was secluded it gave us enough space to roam around for activities. Ioana was so amazing to work with and helped plan all of the little details for our favors and menu. They were flexible and accommodating. Definitely recommend!

—

Best neighborhood brunch spot! The friendliest staff, best service, and the food is sooo good. Have to get the latkes and the chicken schnitzel. Save room for the bakery items. And the espresso martini is delicious.
reviews.author: Justine Dungo

reviews.text:
Had a great brunch at Gertie’s the other day. We came in on a Sunday afternoon. The two of us were able to get a table right away. We ordered the chicken sandwich and pickled veggies. Everything hit the spot. The fries especially were delicious. We also ordered a chocolate babka for the road that was so yummy.
The service was quick and attentive. The interior is bright and comfy. We will definitely be back!
reviews.author: Midori Grabowski

personalization.forUser: Lighthouse's seasonal menu and focus on fresh ingredients might appeal to Alex's interest in quality food experiences.

places.address: 145 Borinquen Pl, Brooklyn, NY 11211, USA

reviews.text:
Visited this spot in Williamsburg recently — loved the focus on fermented ingredients and bold flavors like tahini and harissa. We had two market fish dishes and a few mezze, and the quality was definitely high. Everything tasted super fresh, thoughtfully prepared, and unique.
That said, portions were on the small side for the price (we spent around $90–$100), so just keep that in mind. When we asked if the mezze came with sourdough, the waitress said yes, but then the owner(I assume) asked us to order it separately ($5). Not a big deal, but small gestures like that could go a long way in making guests feel more welcome.
The biggest downside was the noise — it was really loud inside, which made it hard to relax or have a proper conversation. Overall, we loved the food but probably wouldn’t come back just because of the atmosphere.
reviews.author: Beyza Akk

reviews.text: We love this place!! Amazing drinks and food, but our favorite part is Emil - he has made us feel so welcome every time we come. Always remembering us and our orders. He has such incredible energy - really makes us come back time and time again. Highly recommend!!
reviews.author: Sarah Najjar

reviews.text:
I walk past this spot all the time and always notice the laughter and good vibes coming from inside. I'm happy to say, it’s just as pleasant as it looks. The doors were open on this nice day, and we enjoyed a great breeze flowing through.

I had the drink of the day, a blood orange spritz, and it was solid. The food? Also, a win. The chicken shawarma was layered with flavor, so so good. I’ll definitely be coming back for it again. The pita? Fresh, fluffy and just right.

Bonus points for accepting InKind and Blackbird. That alone sealed the deal for a return visit.
reviews.author: Takyashilah S

personalization.forUser: Casa Ora serves Italian food, one of Alex's favorite cuisines.

places.address: 148 Meserole St, Brooklyn, NY 11206, USA

reviews.text: The atmosphere felt very intimate, it was dark but inviting and a great spot for a date. Service was phenomenal, they were very attentive and gave great recommendations. The cocktails were a 9/10, I had a spicy mango drink. The arepas were incredible but the number one dish was the bollitos pelones. Highly recommended. The baby shark dish was our least favorite but each dish was plated with care and very aesthetically pleasing.
reviews.author: Jonny Loero

reviews.text: Tried Venezuelan food for the first time and it didn’t disappoint. The whole spot had a warm vibe with a really inviting ambiance. Drinks were flavorful and a little strong in a good way. The food was the star though. The red snapper on tostones was fire, perfect coating and great flavor. The brisket with black beans and egg was incredibly flavorful and the meat was super tender. Overall, a really nice experience.
reviews.author: Joshua Dyer

reviews.text:
We went to Casa Ora last night to celebrate my birthday, and I’m still thinking about every single bite. The asado negro alone deserves its own love letter. If you’ve never had it, imagine a piece of beef that has been brined, marinated, and slow-cooked for hours until it becomes as tender as butter, then finished with a deep, glossy caramelization of papelón that gives you that slightly charred, smoky sweetness. It is the kind of dish that stops conversation at the table, an art piece with soul.

And everything else? Perfection with nostalgia woven in.
The plantains, the mini cachapas, the tequeños, and a pan de jamón so good it could make your abuela cry, warm, tender, slightly sweet, salty, comforting. Every plate felt like someone was inviting us into their home, letting us taste the food their family grew up on, the food that fills the kitchen on a Sunday afternoon.

Casa Ora is full of heart. You can feel the love, the purpose, the passion in every corner, not just in the dishes but in the way the team carries themselves. It is rare to find a place that feeds you and moves you at the same time.

This is the restaurant you will rave about.
The one you will bring friends to, brag about, and keep thinking about long after you leave.

An unforgettable meal, and a perfect birthday.
Thank you, Casa Ora. 💛
reviews.author: U by Dr Jones

personalization.forUser: While French, Juliette offers a charming ambiance and a diverse menu that could potentially cater to Alex's preferences.

places.address: 135 N 5th St, Brooklyn, NY 11249, USA

reviews.text:
The place is lovely, went on a sunny late morning and the skylight was charming. The staff was super friendly, but u found food a little dry for my taste. However my boyfriend enjoyed it so it might be on me. Had the poached eggs and those were really good.
There’s also a rooftop; looked nice but only saw it on the way out. Will try next time
reviews.author: Ioana Popa

reviews.text: Freakin' loved this place. Wife go the french dip & I got the banana french toast. Maybe a top 10 french toast I've ever had. The caramelized banana. The candied walnuts. The smoked bourbon syrup. It all worked so perfectly together. Would 100% order again.
reviews.author: Nick McCaskill

reviews.text:
This place is super cute, it is kind of like a slightly downmarket version of Majorelle on the upper east side. The decor is very similar, with plants everywhere coming from the ceiling. The temperature inside was very good. Fans inside give a breeze and not too cold.

The food was exceptional. I have the spicy lamb burger, with no English muffin and it came with really good fries and sauce for everything. The burger was perfect it was tender but firm and the goat cheese was not raw which is usually the down side of ordering a burger with goat cheese.

My boyfriend says he liked the eggs Benedict and it was “fire” and he “wants to stay here”. (Not sure what that means exactly) Unfortunately rooftop isn’t opened. Only on weekends.

The drinks are good too we had Bloody Maria with tequila, one with Mexcal and Rose.

Our waiter was Diego. He was amazing on point and very friendly. He had at least ten tables and he isn’t breaking a sweat.

Overall I definitely recommend it and also go on the weekend so you can go the rooftop.
reviews.author: Julia Gaines

personalization.forUser: While not directly aligning with Alex's cuisine preferences, Hole In The Wall Williamsburg could offer some interesting dishes that align with their adventurous spirit.

places.address: 292 Bedford Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11249, USA

reviews.text:
Yesterday, while walking past several restaurants, I found myself craving an exceptional meal and was immediately drawn to the menu at Hole in the Wall. We were seated right away, and the menu offered an impressive selection that truly set high expectations.

We began with the sausage rolls and wings, both of which were equally outstanding. For our entrées, we each ordered the OG Burger, and it did not disappoint. The use of ground short rib for the burger patties was an excellent choice, resulting in rich flavor and perfect texture. Every element was expertly prepared—the seasoning was spot on, the cheese melted beautifully, the bacon was crisp, the vegetables were fresh, and even the fries stood out.

It is rare to find a restaurant where every dish excels, but Hole in the Wall delivered across the board. The staff was warm, attentive, and professional, and the relaxed atmosphere added to an already outstanding dining experience.
reviews.author: McKeith

reviews.text: Really nice atmosphere!  Open and airy with good food and very friendly and excellent people that work here!  I had the smash burger which was awesome!  The food comes very quickly and is presented really well!  The gentleman that took care of us ruled and we will definitely come back!  Hope to try some of the other items on the menu!  Also, the bathroom is super clean and really well done.  If you’re in the area try this spot out for a casual meal, you won’t regret it!
reviews.author: Mark Monstroski

reviews.text:
Came on a saturday morning for brunch.
We got pork benedict, cheddar omelete, breakfast burrito, and dulce de leche. Loved everything! Would go back! Service was fast and snappy.

Make sure you get reservations. The place gets pretty busy.
reviews.author: SC

personalization.forUser: K'far offers a unique brunch experience with a focus on Israeli cuisine, which might appeal to Alex's adventurous side.

places.address: 97 Wythe Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11249, USA

reviews.text: Beautiful interior and amazing food. I’ve been to their location in Philly and this one here in Brooklyn did not disappoint. Came for Saturday brunch. The Jerusalem bagel, Shakshuka, and blueberry pancakes were all very delicious! Also love the Yemenite latte. Great service. Would definitely recommend to anyone who is looking for a great brunch spot.
reviews.author: Chris C

reviews.text:
Honestly had a very underwhelming experience at this restaurant. The highlight of the meal was the appetizers- the lamb tartar was really good but it was extremely greasy and did not have enough to cut on the oil and grease.

I was not a fan of the baba ganoush and the smoked hamachi crudo. The hamachi was extremely fishy and did not taste fresh at all. The lamb could have had more flavor, and the brick chicken was dry.

the ambiance was really nice though with the dim lighting!

The apple olive oil cake was pretty dense as well. It was too dense and not light enough- what we thought an olive oil cake should taste like.

The service was great though. Overall it was decent, was not too impressed for the price. Would not come again.
reviews.author: Jessica Wong

reviews.text:
This place is so warm and personal yet stylish and elegant, we love it. The food is imaginative and well made.
The lamb shank is out of this world- nice crust, falling off the bone, in cherry sauce - one of the best things we ate this year.
We were treated to a grilled halloumi in blueberry sauce with pistachios that was a perfect balance of sweet and tart and savory.
reviews.author: Tania StGeorge

personalization.forUser: Sunday in Brooklyn is a popular brunch spot known for its innovative dishes and lively atmosphere, potentially aligning with Alex's interest in trendy experiences.

places.address: 348 Wythe Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11249, USA

reviews.text: The service amazing. For 2 people they offered a 2 person table, outside or inside, they sat us right away. The food was Fast and tasted fresh. Eggs were done perfectly, soft scrambled, bacon crispy, potatoes were a little too salty, and the shakshuka was a little disappointing, like salsa with pouched eggs, but the bread was crisp and yummy when dipped into the bowl. However, the Sunday pancake was amazing. It’s was like a mini fluffy yellow cake with delicious buttered maple all over. not a maple taste but like a chocolaty buttery nutty flavor. “It was like a reward”. We enjoyed it the most. Overall we understand the hype and definitely recommend to try it for yourself.
reviews.author: Mar Ta

reviews.text:
I've been to Sunday in Brooklyn several times for both brunch and dinner. Brunch certainly gets busy but its a fun time - make a reservation. The food, service and drinks are always lovely - Thomas the bartender is incredible!
I recommend trying the Sage Fright brunch cocktail, the Wood Roasted Half Chicken for dinner and the S'mores soft serve for dessert. The S'mores latte is fun too for all the s'mores fans.
reviews.author: Ryan Woodcox

reviews.text:
Visited Sunday in Brooklyn for brunch and honestly, wow. We got the pistachio hummus with wood-fired flatbread — probably the richest, most flavorful meze I’ve ever had. A total must-try (and so generous we couldn’t even finish it!).

Also ordered the warm grain bowl, and it arrived in what felt like 5 minutes — unbelievably fast service. The bowl itself was pure comfort: warm, rich, and beautifully balanced. The eggs were cooked like a soufflé — soft and melting — topped with a gigantic half avocado and a generous handful of pepitas (which I love and rarely see done this well). The rice underneath was so delicious.

Finished with a cappuccino, served instantly in a lovely porcelain cup — the perfect touch to end brunch.

Our server was incredibly kind and attentive, checking in often to make sure everything was perfect. Honestly, one of the best brunch experiences we’ve had in
reviews.author: Beyza Akk

personalization.forUser: Cafe Mogador offers a Mediterranean-inspired menu, which could appeal to Alex's interest in diverse culinary experiences.

places.address: 133 Wythe Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11249, USA

reviews.text:
I had an outstanding experience at this Mediterranean-inspired restaurant. We ordered several mezze to share, and honestly, they were probably the best I’ve ever had. Everything was incredibly fresh, flavorful, and perfectly executed. The bread alone was amazing.

The service was impressively fast — we were served in under ten minutes — without ever feeling rushed. We started with wine, then had coffee, and I finished with a cocktail, which was excellent as well. Every part of the experience flowed seamlessly.

We sat at the bar, which added to the experience. The staff was extremely kind and attentive, the atmosphere felt cozy yet refined — luxurious without being over the top. You can really feel the quality and care in every detail. Even the restrooms were spotless.

An impeccable experience from start to finish. I will definitely come back and highly recommend this place without hesitation.

reviews.text:

reviews.text: Being my first time in New York City I was taken to a quaint little Mexican restaurant in Brooklyn. Now coming from Los Angeles where we have exceptional Mexican food all over the city. Try some outside of California is a bit of a treat. Oxomoco has some very good dishes on an elevated level. They use high quality ingredients for all there dishes lending to elevated taste. The fish tacos were great tender flaky fish with a nice not too spicy slaw on top. Chips and salsa that had multiple levels of heat you get five salsas to try. The crab tostada was nice a flavorful and the wagyu beef cheek were tender with a nice mole sauce. They also have a nice mix of tequila and mezcal drinks for you to choose from. The menu is small but has something for everyone. All the dishes we had were very delicious and the atmosphere was great. Indoor and patio dining is available. Oh make sure you make  reservations so you don’t have to wait if you want inside. If you’re in Brooklyn swing by and give them a try. You won’t be disappointed.

reviews.text: My boyfriend and I had an amazing dinner at Oxomoco—our second visit, and it felt just as special. Chef Maria and her team were wonderful. We started with the guac and chips; the tortillas were perfectly crisp and the guacamole was vibrant and flavorful. The soy-marinated tostada was a standout—the aguachile salsa had a spicy kick but was incredibly addictive. For tacos, the maitake was deeply savory, the shrimp tacos were crunchy and well-seasoned, and the pork carnitas were fun to assemble and packed with flavor.

reviews.text:
The bar is located on the top floor of the Ritz Carlton hotel. So as soon as you walk in, it’s lovely. Once you go up the elevator and get off, you’re greeted with a very chic host area. I came on a Friday and had reservations for  4:30. We wanted to time our reservation for a sunset view. The views of the city are stunning and truly one of the focal points as soon as you walk in, which is great if you’re someone who loves a photo op. The space is very Instagramable.
After we checked in with the hostess we were guided to the bar to order a drink while waiting for our table. The bar is very spacious with comfortable seating and friendly and attentive staff.
Once our table was ready we were brought over to a nice booth along the wall with a good view of the whole place. We were promptly greeted by our server, Johnathan. We had some questions about the menu that he answered with ease and even gave us good recommendations. I’m a dirty martini girl, but my mom and sister took his recommendations and absolutely loved their cocktails. We also ordered some food and I wish I could have eaten 10 more of the tuna rolls. They are delicious and I dream about them. I’ll just have to come back the next time I’m in New York.
reviews.author: Danielle Verble

reviews.text:
I recently tried the high tea at Nubeluz, and it turned out to be a memorable and beautifully executed experience. Nubeluz is known for its skyline views and modern atmosphere, and those elements definitely elevate the high tea. The moment you walk in, you’re greeted with a panoramic sweep of Manhattan that immediately sets a luxurious tone. The space feels contemporary and stylish, very different from the traditional settings you find in classic afternoon teas.

The food was excellent — thoughtful, refined, and visually impressive. The savory bites had clean flavors, and the pastries were delicate without being overly sweet. Everything tasted fresh, and the presentation added to the experience. The tea selection was also quite good, and the staff were helpful in guiding us through the choices. Service was attentive but relaxed, giving the experience a more modern lounge feel.

Compared to The Ritz in London, the difference is clear but enjoyable in its own way. The Ritz is all about tradition, ceremony, and formality — the classic tiered trays, the live music, and the unmistakable old-world charm. Nubeluz, on the other hand, feels contemporary, sleek, and more playful. Instead of ornate décor and formal tea service, you get dramatic city views and a stylish, cosmopolitan vibe.

The Ritz London focuses on preserving an elegant ritual, while Nubeluz offers a reinterpretation of afternoon tea that fits New York’s energy. Both are excellent experiences, but they appeal to different moods: the Ritz when you want classic refinement, and Nubeluz when you’re in the mood for something modern with a bit of sparkle.

Overall, high tea at Nubeluz is a beautiful, delicious, and uniquely New York experience, and it stands strong even when compared with iconic high teas abroad.
reviews.author: Alok Tewari

reviews.text:
Nubeluz is an incredible rooftop experience! The views are stunning from every angle.
Such a wonderful afternoon tea experience! The presentation was beautiful — fresh sandwiches, warm scones, and a lovely selection of pastries, The small bites were delicious and paired perfectly with the drinks.

The tea was fragrant and perfectly brewed, with plenty of flavors to choose from. The atmosphere was elegant and relaxing, and the staff were attentive and friendly, making the whole experience feel special. A perfect spot to unwind and enjoy a classy, delicious afternoon tea. Definitely a must-visit spot for amazing experiences and unforgettable view.
