reviews.text:
Celebrating New Year’s Eve 2026 at 230 Fifth Rooftop was nothing short of spectacular—and truly a once-in-a-lifetime experience. From the moment we arrived, it was clear that getting a table was the best decision we could have made. Having appetizers and a bottle delivered directly to our table as part of the package elevated the entire night and allowed us to relax and fully enjoy the celebration without fighting crowds. The layout was incredibly well thought out: despite being a packed NYE event, it never felt uncomfortably crowded. There were endless photo opportunities with the iconic skyline as the backdrop, making every moment feel special and memorable.

The energy throughout the night was electric. The DJs were phenomenal, keeping the vibe high and the party going nonstop. A huge shout-out to our waiter, Abu Karim, who was absolutely outstanding—attentive, professional, and on top of everything all night long. His service alone made the experience feel seamless and VIP. The open bar was fantastic, and the round rooftop igloos were such a cool touch—easy to access, warm, and perfect for enjoying drinks while taking in the views. Even better, they provided robes for guests who wanted to stay outside on the rooftop, proving that they truly thought of every detail.

Coming all the way from California, spending New Year’s Eve in New York City was a bucket-list dream—and this night at 230 Fifth was the cherry on top. From start to finish, it exceeded every expectation imaginable. Thoughtful planning, incredible atmosphere, top-tier service, and unforgettable memories made this a 10/10 experience. I would absolutely do it again without hesitation and highly recommend it to anyone looking to ring in the New Year in the most iconic way possible.

reviews.text: The theme is very cute here! It was decorated with cherries for summer on a rooftop with great golden hour sun and nice city views. The lite bites were tasty (we loved the Mac & cheese balls!!! We wish the chicken bites had more than 1 dipping sauce, but they were still good). The spicy cherry Paloma was delicious!! The cherry espresso martini tasted a bit like medicine. Our waitress was so nice and helpful, but the bus boys were very rude - they kept trying to rush us and clear our table even though it was not busy, it was half empty, so it’s not like they needed to clear our table. Also, we genuinely felt very judged for taking photos, even though we were just at our table in the corner. One bus boy kept giving us nasty looks, which I’ve never experienced at a city rooftop bar that is designed for photo taking. The same bus boy made me move my bag off a tiny side table (RIGHT next to my seat) so he could give it to a larger party, but when I looked on the other side of the group, I saw an empty side table that he could have grabbed instead. I would definitely would return to check out the next theme & get another Paloma! But now I know how some staff is about photos and service. Just be warned, the cherry tunnel is used to get to seats and to take pictures there, you might block staff, so you have to snap quickly when they’re not walking around. It’s not a side area that you can pose for a ton of pictures to avoid getting in the way, which feels a little silly for a place that heavily advertises all the photo opportunities.

reviews.text: The views are amazing, the cocktails are good but not top notch. The best time to come is sunset time and usually there is a queue so I recommend coming 30-60 mins in advance. This will allow you to enjoy the sunset followed by the view on New York at night. They have minimum one cocktail per person policy and ask you for a credit card at the entrance. You then need to give them your last name every time you order which is really not super convenient from the one hand, but allows you to easily move around the place on another. They have two storeys and both closed space as well as the open terrace. The views are almost 360 degrees and are just outstanding. The velvet green cocktail was just okay - had some aftertaste and was a bit sour. Fragolina was probably the nicest one I’ve tried - with a very simple yet tasty flavour. The only downside was that it was a bit bitter. S.D.G. tasted a bit sour/fermented and even though I love mezcal, I was not a big fan of the cocktail itself. Some staff members were slightly haughty. Overall I recommend this place if you are in New York - the views compensate for everything that is not perfect. I am usually not a huge atmosphere advocate and usually come to bars and restaurants for food and drinks but this is one of the cases when the atmosphere really boosts the experience

reviews.text:

reviews.text:
We were looking for a sandwich spot after our visit to the nearby Whitney Museum for the museum Friday nights. It was about 930 pm and this spot was still open. We were lucky to find a free parking spot just around the corner.

First impression, as others have said, it is very cozy. Pleasant welcoming environment inside, there was plenty of tables inside and we decided to take a seat. A lot to look at in the restaurant. Much merchandising and a Tv in the corner playing scenes from Italy. All very beautiful and nostalgic. Did I feel like I may have been transported to Italy for a minute? Yes, I think so.

The sandwiches are reasonably priced and we went with a Chicken parm and meatball parm. I didn’t go with one of the bread options for an extra cost. We also went with the Italian sodas.
The sandwhiches were bountiful and very filling.  Artisanal if that makes sense. Delicious too.

Now the criticism. As I always point out. I have a thing about restaurant front doors. This one stayed open and it was cold and windy outside. I’m glad I decided to sit on the bench seat but if I hadn’t I would have the wind blowing on me. Another gripe. These delivery drivers picking up orders. They ruin the dining vibe coming in, leaving the door open, talking on their phones, dressed like dirty slobs. All in black, helmets on, face covered, did I say dirty, and no regard to diners. It really takes away from the experience.

reviews.text:
St Tropez West Village is nothing short of magical - it’s cozy and romantic with big bay windows and a rustic homey feel.  Very well done French bistro cuisine.  Love the hanger steak and scallops.  And the desserts… save room and splurge, you will not regret it.  Food, service and wine selection - all are above and beyond.  If you are looking for a cute, classy West Village date spot, this is it!  Book one of the super cute bay windows that look out on West 4th Street.  It’s dreamy… P.s. I’ve been many times. Read on for a personal story and if you’d like to know more :)

Most recent visit was this Wednesday before Thanksgiving.  I called the restaurant to book one very specific window bay, and I enlisted their help in proposing to my now fiancée!  We had our first date here and I wanted to recreate our first date. Yohann and Ali and their staff pulled out all the stops to make our evening perfect, from setting up our table with photos and capturing our moment, to letting us celebrate well after the last patrons had left, and like I said, always save room for dessert here.  The chocolate mousse can change your world.  I hadn’t met the owner and management until this week, but they insisted on treating us to champagne, several desserts, honestly, it was too kind.  St Tropez is a West Village neighborhood gem that will warm your heart and satisfy your palate.

reviews.text:
Hands-on most beautiful state park in New York has preserved the legacy of park’s founders Smiley brothers by maintaining the carriage roads and trails in excellent state.
My favorite loop is to follow Castle road to Lake Awosting and return back via Hamilton road back to Minnewasca lake. Very scenic views that don’t require serious hiking effort, just slight inclines and declines.
Natural beauty of Shawangunk Mountains here is supplemented by road building prowess of preserve’s founders and is the reason that we still have the park available now to thousands of daily visitors at a modest fee. Many grand historic hotels of Catskills don’t exist anymore including burnt out Cliff House and Windmere hotels previously located at shores of Lake Minnewasca till 1970s, so really glad that conservation efforts have succeeded here.
New visitor center and expansive parking lots are huge improvement over park’s facilities of just six years ago.

reviews.text:
Visited: Friday, October 24, 2025

I hiked the Castle Point Loop starting from the Upper Parking Lot. The parking lot was spacious and not crowded — definitely past the peak season — and parking was $10. The weather was a bit chilly, but the fall colors were still beautiful.

At first, I took the UA trail toward Castle Point, but it was mostly gravel and not very exciting. Later I switched to the BR trail, which was better, though I hardly saw anyone the entire time — maybe fewer than five people total.

The hike itself felt a bit monotonous; even on the way down, it was just gravel again, so I ended up jogging down. I remembered Gertrude’s Nose being much more interesting and scenic in comparison.

I stopped by the Falls at the end, but honestly, it wasn’t something I’d go out of my way to see again. Overall, it’s a decent hike for solitude and views, but not one I’d rush to repeat — especially considering it takes around 5 hours round trip.

There are some stone stairs you can take as a shortcut to to the Sam's Point lookout but the path goes straight to too.

From there you can walk a little under a mile to get to Lake Maritanza or the path to the ice caves.

The ice caves were pretty amazing, perfectly cool on a warm late summer day. Be sure to have good shoes as there are some rocky scrambles and a few ladders to climb up.

reviews.text:
What a wild adventure! We hiked Peanut Leap Cascade and tackled the Giant Stairs Trail at Palisades Interstate Park—and it started off sunny and beautiful. But halfway through, a sudden flood storm came rolling in. The skies turned dark, rain poured down, and we even heard the emergency sirens go off three times.

The trail, already challenging with its boulder scrambles and steep terrain, became even more intense in the rain. It was tough, slippery, and at times a little nerve-wracking, but also incredibly exhilarating. The waterfall at Peanut Leap was stunning, especially with all the extra rainfall, and the views of the Hudson were dramatic and unforgettable.

This hike is no joke, especially in unexpected weather. But if you’re up for an adventurous challenge and come prepared, it’s an experience you’ll never forget. Just be sure to check the forecast—and maybe have an exit plan just in case!

reviews.text:
Sterling Lake, named for the silvery barked beach trees in this area, is located off Sterling Mine  Road on Old Forge Rd. I must admit, it's somewhat confusing the way the nearby lakes are named. We are referring to Sterling Lake. There are also Little Sterling Lake and Sterling Forest Lake(also called Blue Lake on the IBM Corporate Office Park. IBM's nickname is "Big Blue"). Mining for iron in this area was taking place before the Revolutionary War. The links of chain across the Hudson River to prevent British warships from sailing past West Point were made in the original foundry at Sterling Mine. It was intended to halt progress of warships. Cannon placements in West Point and strategic hill tops would lob cannon shot  down onto the stranded vessels. This was a physically impractical engineering design the chain failing under its own weight. And British naval strategists knew how risky a notion it would be to travel up the Hudson River while the Continental Army held such a strategic and formidable fortress. It was a stalemate. But the mines held an important place for it made the weapons needed to win the war.
Mine shafts travel under thIs lake. It is a watershed. It's clean water is part of the Hudson Highlands Watershed and provides water for reservoirs below it. Hiking, mountain biking and cross country skiing trails are available for use in this 20,000 acre park. The Frank Lautenburg Visitors Center and parking area sits on a prominence on the south side of the lake. You could hike the lake and many connected trails from here or take a short walk to see the restored  original blast furnace or crumbling remains of later iron works operations.  But now to the present.  Last year, two climate related events devastated Sterling Forest and its trails are closed indefinitely. There is no time line for remediating damage here. A May, 2024 violent change of season storm brought the jet stream tumbling to earth, which destroyed the forest as though it was a clear cutting operation. We spoke to  a sawyer by the visitors center. Brian was his name and he told us to look at his YouTube videos of what he does. Just Google Brian NV to see his videos. He hikes miles into the woods to open trails with  a chain saw. Then, on November 9, 2024, after a long drought, the Jenkins fire scorched the area. It was a quick moving forest fire that may actually be beneficial to old growth trees by removing underbrush that can choke and rob these trees of nutrients. But it's a nice ride to get here and see the big blow down and mine operations and visitor center displays of dioramas, mine artifacts and wildlife.
